                    <msContents>
                        <summary>A manuscript copy of the anatomical sections of an early
                            14th-century work by <persName>Kajiwara Shōzen</persName>, possibly
                                <title xml:lang="ja-Latn" source="IANA">Ton’ishō</title> | <title
                                xml:lang="ja" source="IANA">頓医抄</title>, containing polychrome and
                            line illustrations showing internal organs and acupuncture charts, with
                            text in katakana-majiri. The cover, which gives the title <title
                                xml:lang="ja" source="IANA">五臓六府十二経脉</title>, is not contemporary
                            with the text and was added later.</summary>

                        <textLang mainLang="ja" source="IANA">Japanese</textLang>

                        <msItem n="1" xml:id="Japanese_16">
                            <author key="person_18764240" source="VIAF">
                                <persName xml:lang="ja" source="IANA">梶原性全</persName>
                                <persName xml:lang="ja-Latn" source="IANA">Kajiwara
                                    Shōzen</persName>
                                <note><p><persName>Kajiwara Shōzen</persName>,<date from="1266"
                                            to="1337">1266-1337</date>, was a Buddhist monk and
                                        doctor who lived in <placeName>Kamakura</placeName>, to the
                                        south of modern <placeName>Tokyo</placeName>. His <title
                                            xml:lang="ja-Latn" source="IANA">Ton’ishō</title> |
                                            <title xml:lang="ja" source="IANA">頓医抄</title> and
                                            <title xml:lang="ja-Latn" source="IANA">Man’anpō</title>
                                        | <title xml:lang="ja" source="IANA">万安方</title> are the two
                                        best-known medical treatises of the <date from="1192"
                                            to="1333">Kamakura period</date>: the former, unusually
                                        for the time, was written in katakana-majiri so as to be
                                        more accessible and thus help alleviate suffering, while the
                                        latter was written in kanbun and was thus aimed at fellow
                                        medical scholars. Both cover the whole range of medicine as
                                        it was known at the time and show the author’s extensive
                                        familiarity with Chinese medical literature, but neither
                                        work was printed before modern times.</p></note>
                            </author>

                            <title type="gedai">
                                <title type="main" xml:lang="ja" source="IANA">五臓六府十二経脉</title>
                                <title type="alt" xml:lang="ja-Latn" source="IANA">Gozō roppu
                                    jūnikeimyaku</title>
                                <title type="alt" xml:lang="en" source="IANA">The meridians with the
                                    five viscera and six bowels</title>
                                <note><p>外題: The title is taken from the outside cover.</p></note>
                            </title>

                            <filiation><p>Illustrations of dissections were derived from a lost
                                    Chinese work on the dissection of executed prisoners, <title
                                        xml:lang="alalc97" source="IANA">Cunzhen huanzong tu</title>
                                    | <title xml:lang="ja" source="IANA">存真環中図</title>,
